# Chapter 7 — Spirits of the Earth (Nalanda & Patna, India)

*Keeper-facing summary of Chapter 7 of The Children of Fear. Structure lives in
the sibling `.arc`, stat blocks in the `.actor`, campaign lore in
`children-of-fear-0.4-campaign-overview.lore`. Consult your copy of the campaign
for full text, read-aloud passages, and handouts. Second chapter of the linear
Climax phase (see the campaign `FLOW`).*

## Role in the campaign

The ritual-site chapter. The party returns to the heart of ancient India —
**Nalanda** and **Patna** (old Pataliputra) in Bihar — to reach the fabled **Hell
Chambers built by Emperor Ashoka**, and to descend into that underworld to prepare
and secure what the rite against the King of Fear requires. It ties together the
campaign's Ashoka/Buddhist-history thread and delivers a set-piece dungeon of
horror beneath the earth.

## Setting

**Bihar** — birthplace of Buddhism. **Nalanda**, the great ancient Buddhist
monastic university, and **Patna/Pataliputra**, seat of the Mauryan empire. The
looming feature is the legend of **Ashoka** — as the ruthless "Chandashoka" before
his conversion he is said to have built hidden **Hell Chambers** and destroyed his
rival brothers there (the "Unfair"), before becoming the great Buddhist emperor.

## Structure and key beats

**The Heart of an Empire.** Ashoka's history and the significance of the Hell
Chambers as the campaign's ritual locus.

**Spreading the Word.** The investigators' approach and the local/historical
context around Patna and Nalanda.

**Descent into the Underworld.** The party enters Ashoka's subterranean Hell
Chambers — a dangerous dungeon of the dead beneath a temple compound.

**The Yakshini.** A guardian spirit — a **Yakshini** and her venomous snakes (born
from mango seeds) — defends the depths; a signature supernatural encounter of the
chapter.

## Key NPCs & threats

- **The Yakshini** and her snakes — the underworld guardian. (Stat blocks in the `.actor`.)
- **Tenzin Kalsang / the Tokabhaya** — the lama's rite drives the descent; the
  antagonists press toward the endgame.

## Clues & handouts (as information)

- Chapter handouts and the regional *What Your Investigator Knows* material for
  Bihar / India.

## Keeper guidance

- Frame the Hell Chambers with Ashoka's before-and-after arc (tyrant to
  world-renouncing emperor) — it mirrors the campaign's themes of fear and
  liberation.
- The Yakshini set-piece is the chapter's climax gate; play the underworld as a
  Sanity-eroding descent.

## Transition

With the underworld business done, the Climax continues into Chapter 8 (*The Heart
of the World*), where the ritual is finally enacted.
